version: 4.22, commit https://git.eclipse.org/c/jdt/eclipse.jdt.ui.git/commit/?id=a8e3244e6579dcfc19dc4db727589e9ce9b67ee5
                A related issue - https://github.com/eclipse/eclipse.jdt.ls/issues/1899

                Steps to reproduce:

                - open the following class
                import java.io.Serializable;

                public class Test3 implements Serializable {

                }
                - call Quick Fix)Add default serial version ID
                - you will get
                import java.io.Serializable;

                public class Test3 implements Serializable {

                /**
                *
                */
                private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

                }

When an autocloseable resource is missing a close:

                public class TestMissingTryWithResources {

                public void foo() throws IOException {
                BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("a.b"));
                br.markSupported();
                }

                }

                br will be noted as having a resource leak. There is no current quick fix for surrounding with try-with-resources though a quick assist is offered for the same
                line.

The following tests fail to surround fileReader declarations with try-with-resources quick assist:

                public void foo2() throws IOException {
                final File file = new File("somefile");
                final FileReader fileReader = new FileReader(file);
                char[] in = new char[50];
                fileReader.read(in);
                new Runnable() {
                public void run() {
                try {
                fileReader.close();
                FileReader localReader = new FileReader(file);
                } catch (IOException ex) { /* nop */ }
                }}.run();
                }

                public void foo3(boolean f1, boolean f2) throws IOException {
                File file = new File("somefile");
                if (f1) {
                FileReader fileReader = new FileReader(file);
                char[] in = new char[50];
                fileReader.read(in);
                while (true) {
                FileReader loopReader = new FileReader(file);
                loopReader.close();
                break;
                }
                } else {
                FileReader fileReader = new FileReader(file);
                if (f2)
                fileReader.close();
                }
                }

Since 4.21, the type filter java.awt.* has been added and is enabled by default (see bug 571758).

                Unfortunately, the AWT API is exposed/used in Swing, for example by javax.swing.JFrame extending java.awt.Frame, by javax.swing.JComponent extending
                java.awt.Component which provides the method getBounds() that returns a java.awt.Rectangle, etc.

                There is also java.awt.Robot contained in AWT without there being an alternative for that in Swing or somewhere else.

                Samples:

                class Sample extends javax.swing.JFrame {
                void init() {
                | // (- here no proposal for "setSize(...)"
                }
                void foo(javax.swing.JFrame jFrame) {
                jFrame.| // (- here no proposal for "setSize(...)"
                }
                void bounds() {
                this.getBounds().| // (- here no proposal for "x"
                }
                void robot() {
                new Rob| // (- here no proposal for "Robot"
                }
                }

                A couple of questions were asked on Stack Overflow because of this (most are closed as duplicate of the first; some might already be deleted):
                - https://stackoverflow.com/q/69357171/6505250 (JFrame)
                - https://stackoverflow.com/q/69515233/6505250 (Rectangle)
                - https://stackoverflow.com/q/69511421/6505250 (Graphics)
                - https://stackoverflow.com/q/69509896/6505250 (BorderLayout)
                - https://stackoverflow.com/q/69393367/6505250 (JFrame)
                - https://stackoverflow.com/q/69415574/6505250 (JFrame)
                - https://stackoverflow.com/q/69399195/6505250 (BorderLayout)
                - ...

                I suggest removing the type filter "java.awt.*" or at least disabling it by default.
                Instead, I would like to have "java.awt.List" filtered by default.

Instead of writing String.valuOf('a'), "Join" cleanup should write "a".

                Given:
                boolean isFirst = true;
                StringBuilder concatenation = new StringBuilder();

                for (String text : texts) {
                if (isFirst) {
                isFirst = false;
                } else {
                concatenation = concatenation.append(',');
                }
                concatenation = concatenation.append(text);
                }

                return concatenation.toString();

                When:
                Clean up the code enabling "Uses String.join() when possible"

                Then:
                String concatenation= String.join(",", texts);

                return concatenation;

                It also allows not hard-coded delimiters if the delimiter is immutable.

AFAICS the cursor position for the new lambda expression could be improve or tab could be supported to jump to the code block.

                Example:

                @Test
                void numberFieldsetWrongValueType() {
                String testString = "testString";
                assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class, CODE_COMPLETION_HERE)
                }

                I get:

                @Test
                void numberFieldsetWrongValueType() {
                String testString = "testString";
                assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class, CURSOR_HERE()-));
                }

                IMHO it would be better if the cursor could be after the -) or if I could jump to this position with tab.

If the entire body of a lambda expression is selected then it cannot be extracted to a method. An error says that the selection is not valid. This is not
                the case with the body of an if statement for example.

                public void foo(Object parent) {
                List(String) a = new ArrayList()();
                if (parent instanceof Composite) {
                ((Composite) parent).addDisposeListener(e -) {
                a.add("abc");
                a.add("def");
                });
                }

                }

                In the code example, attemtping to select from paren to paren surrounding the a.add statements or if the Shift+alt+up is used to select the whole block, extract to
                method will not work either as quick assist or via the Refactoring menu.

The rule will remove parenthesis on a if with negation :

                if (!(expression)) =) if (!expression)

                However if the expression is a Java 16 instanceof pattern matching, removing the parenthesis results into a compilation errror "The operator ! is undefined for the
                argument type(s) x" where x is the variable in the following if statement:

                if(!(x instanceof Employee e)) {

                }

                The parenthesis must be kept when this pattern is matched.

The affected equals method can be found in org.eclipse.jdt.internal.ui.packageview.ClassPathContainer$RequiredProjectWrapper.

                The code after the second if statement (see below) is never reached. This causes that duplicate project dependencies appear in our Eclipse project.

                public boolean equals(Object obj) {
                if (this == obj)
                return true;
                if (obj == null || obj!=this)
                return false;
                if (getClass() != obj.getClass())
                return false;
                RequiredProjectWrapper other= (RequiredProjectWrapper) obj;
                if (!Objects.equals(fClasspathEntry, other.fClasspathEntry)) {
                return false;
                }
                if (!Objects.equals(fParent, other.fParent)) {
                return false;
                }
                if (!Objects.equals(fProject, other.fProject)) {
                return false;
                }
                return true;
                }

Take the following example

                public interface A {
                void foo();
                }

                public class AImpl implements A {
                public void foo() {
                System.out.println();
                }
                }


                public class B {
                private A handler;

                public avoid callFoo() {
                handler.foo();

                }

                }


                invoking the callee hierarchy on the callFoo method. I would expect to see the hierarchy with AImpl.foo. Today's implementation stops at A.foo.

                This is probably due to we don't know which implementation to expand on if there are multiple implementations.

                But as a starting point could we expand if we only see one subtype, may be that solution can be improved in future to expand on demand for selected subtype when
                there are multiple by the user.

When source clean-up adds brackets to a single-line if statement, it removes the comment.

                Example :

                public class Test {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                if (args.length == 0) // no args
                System.out.println("no args");
                }
                }

                Result:

                public class Test {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                if (args.length == 0) {
                System.out.println("no args");
                }
                }
                }

                The comment "no args" vanished with the refactoring.

                The rule is "Use blocks in if/while/for/do" statements under "Code style" tab.

                Version: 2021-12 (4.22.0)
                Build id: 20211202-1639

When I do Source-)Clean-Up on the example below, it results into a compilation failure.

                I selected the 2 following rules:
                - Reduce indentation
                - Merge conditions of if/else if/else that have the same blocks

                Example:

                public class Test {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                if (!(args != null)) {
                System.out.println("null args: we should not be here");
                } else {
                return;
                }
                return;
                }
                }

                Result:

                public class Test {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                if (MISSING) {
                return;
                }
                System.out.println("null args: we should not be here");
                return;
                }
                }


                Moreover, the error could go un-noticed with this modified example (it compiles only by coincidence) :

                public class Test {

                public static final boolean MISSING = true;

                public static void main(String[] args) {
                if (MISSING) {
                return;
                }
                System.out.println("null args: we should not be here");
                return;
                }
                }

When I do Source-)Clean-Up on the following example, it results into compilation failure :

                I selected the rule "Make inner classes static where possible" but in this case it was not possible.

                Example:

                public class Test {
                public Test() {
                this.new Inner();
                }
                class Inner {

                }
                }

                Result:

                public class Test {
                public Test() {
                this.new Inner();
                }
                static class Inner {

                }
                }

                I never use this syntax "this.new", I just happened to find it in org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.classfmt.ModuleInfo.

                There are other rules to remove redundant 'this.' prefixes, and it might be a possible idea to extend them to support this syntax, but if the rule removing the
                prefix is not selected by the user, it will still fail.

When I choose "Convert to switch expression where possible" in Source-)Code Clean-up menu on this example, the assignments end up being discarded.

                Example:


                public class Test {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                boolean rulesOK = true;
                switch (args[0].charAt(0)) {
                case '+':
                args[0] = "+";
                break;
                case '~':
                args[0] = "~";
                break;
                case '-':
                args[0] = "-";
                break;
                case '?':
                args[0] = "?";
                break;
                default:
                rulesOK = false;
                }
                System.out.println(rulesOK);
                }
                }

                Result:


                public class Test {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                boolean rulesOK = true;
                rulesOK = switch (args[0].charAt(0)) {
                case '+' -) "+";
                case '~' -) "~";
                case '-' -) "-";
                case '?' -) "?";
                default -) false;
                };
                System.out.println(rulesOK);
                }
                }

                It also yields a compilation failure due to the type mismatches.

                I believe the sample could be considered non-elligible to the refactoring due to the impossiblity to decide between multiple variables to assign.

                See also : org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.batch.Main.addNewEntry(ArrayList(Classpath), String, ArrayList(String), String, String, boolean, boolean)

Consider the example below (simplified from org.eclipse.osgi.util.NLS.log(int, String, Exception)) :


