When I Choose "Convert to switch expression where possible" in the Source-)Clean-Up menu, the comments end up being discarded.

                Example:

                public class Test {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                boolean isWhiteSpace;
                switch (args[0].charAt(0)) {
                case 10: /* \ u000a: LINE FEED */
                case 12: /* \ u000c: FORM FEED */
                case 13: /* \ u000d: CARRIAGE RETURN */
                case 32: /* \ u0020: SPACE */
                case 9: /* \ u0009: HORIZONTAL TABULATION */
                isWhiteSpace = true;
                break;
                default:
                isWhiteSpace = false;
                }
                System.out.println(isWhiteSpace);
                }
                }

                Result:

                public class Test {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                boolean isWhiteSpace = switch (args[0].charAt(0)) {
                case 10, 12, 13, 32, 9 -) true;
                default -) false;
                };
                System.out.println(isWhiteSpace);
                }
                }

String s = "first\r\n" + "second\r\n" + "third\\";

                This gets converted basically correctly to a text block. However, the backslash in the last string then acts as an escape sequence for the text block ending,
                therefore the result doesn't compile anymore.

                String s = """
                first
                second
                third\""";

                // this is still contained in the text block

                I'm not sure if there is any valid escape sequence to avoid that, so this might be a case where the cleanup just shouldn't do anything, probably.

The different cases of a switch share the same scope of local variables, contrary to if/else blocks.

                Introducing brackets in the cases might be necessay like in the example below:


